\begin{abstract}
An experiment has been conducted to evaluate the
agreement among the sonic anemometers deployed at the ATTO project,
before their final installation at a 325-m high tower. It was
undertaken close to the tall tower location, in a small clearing. A
total of 19 sonic anemometers were compared: 8 \textit{Campbell
  Scientific Instruments} CSAT3Bs and 11 \textit{Thies} Ultrasonic
Anemometer 3Ds. A Planar Fit coordinate rotation was able to identify
the main equivalent slope direction of the streamlines. Previously
recommended shadowing corrections for the CSAT3B are corroborated by
comparison with THIES data, and should applied whenever possible to
ATTO data measured by CSAT3Bs. Likely due to sensor separation, the
THIES measurements agreed among themselves better than CSAT3B
measurements.
\end{abstract}






\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

ATTO \cite[Amazon Tall Tower
  Observatory;][]{andreae.acevedo.ea--atto.overview} is a long-term
monitoring project in the Amazon basin whose main site includes a
325-m tall main lattice tower, an 82-m scaffolding tower, a smaller
80-m lattice tower, a recently deployed ``Campina'' site with
atmospheric \correc{profiling}{remote sensing} instrumentation, and
logistical infrastructure for on-site intensive experiments.  The site
is located at Reserva de Desenvolvimento Sustentável Uatumã, in
Amazonas State, Brazil, 150 km northeast of the state capital Manaus,
at $2^\circ27'$S and $54^\circ10'$W. The canopy height is between 30
and 40 m \citep{diasjr2019classical}.

ATTO is an interdisciplinary experiment whose overall objective is to
better quantify the exchanges of mass {\color{blue}(of several substances such as
$\mathrm{H_2O}$, $\mathrm{CO_2}$, etc.\linelabel{lin:substance})},
momentum and energy between the forest and the atmosphere, with a view
to improve our understanding of the regional atmospheric chemistry,
the weather and climate, and the functioning of the Amazonian
biome. It is generally divided into four highly interactive main
research areas: (i) Micrometeorology and Physical Climate, (ii) Forest
Ecology and Hydrology, (iii) Volatile Organic Compounds, Chemistry,
and (iv) Aerosols, Clouds and Biogeochemistry.

A central constituent of ATTO is the deployment of an array of sonic
anemometers to measure profiles of means and second-order moments of
the wind velocity vector \correc{}{at the 325-m and the 82-m towers}.
The two instruments used are the \textit{Campbell Scientific
  Instruments} CSAT3B (from here on, CSAT3) and the \textit{Thies}
Ultrasonic Anemometer 3D (from here on, THIES).  The measurement
heights in meters above ground are C-005, T-015, C-025, T-035, T-043,
C-050, C-075, C-081, T-100, T-127, T-151, T-172, C-193, C-196, T-223,
T-247, T-274, T-298 and C-316, where C stands for the CSAT3, and T for
the THIES.  {\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-seventwo}Note that these are the heights where the
  instruments were deployed after the experiment described herein. For
the present study, all sensors were deployed at 7.2 m above ground in
a clearing, as described in Section \ref{sec:siteexp}.\linelabel{lin:end-seventwo}}

{\color{blue}\linelabel{lin:begin-objective}The accuracy of these
  profiles depends critically on an absence of bias between the
  measurement levels, because multi-level measurements are necessary
  for the calculation of velocity gradients and to understand how the
  local fluxes themselves and other statistics vary with height ---
  see for example \cite{chor2017flux} and \cite{diasjr2019classical}.
  However, dedicated comparisons of the sonic anemometers used in ATTO
  have not been performed until now.
  %\citep{chor2017flux,diasjr2019classical}.
  Therefore, the main
  objective of the present study is to assess how close the sonic
  anemometers designated to be installed permanently respond to the
  same atmospheric conditions
  %, and to develop confidence in  interpreting profile data measured
  %at the two towers.
  This is particularly difficult in our case because so many
  instruments are involved, so that the comparisons had to be split
  among 4 towers each with 5 or 4 instruments (see Section
  \ref{sec:siteexp}). We refrain, however, from proposing ``best''
  \textit{ad-hoc} corrections among the sonics, and concentrate
  instead on existing proposed corrections in the literature.
  \linelabel{lin:end-objective}}

Sonic anemometers, besides being the mainstay of micrometeorological
research, also provide invaluable data for other research areas, since
they are involved in the direct measurement of prevailing atmospheric
conditions and scalar fluxes between the forest and the atmosphere
\citep{thomas2007organised,dupont2012influence, dupont2012momentum}.
Since their first introduction in field measurements in
micrometeorological campaigns
\citep{kaimal1963continuous,kaimal1963preliminary}, sonic anemometers
have become an essential tool for studying turbulence in the
Atmospheric Boundary Layer. However, in common with any other sensor,
sonic anemometers have limitations that must be understood and taken
into account when interpreting their data.

{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-limitations}Response time, although quite satisfactory to measure turbulence
velocity fluctuations, is not high enough to measure their
derivatives, precluding direct estimates of the TKE
\correc{}{(turbulence kinetic energy)} dissipation rate.  Due to sonic
path length, of the order of 10--20 cm between pairs of transducers,
path averaging also impacts the measured signals
\citep{horst.oncley--correctionstoinertial,freire2019effects}.
\correc{Even if much higher measurement frequencies were attained,
  path averaging would still affect the measurement of
  derivatives.}{However, it affects mostly inertial subrange behavior
  and the estimation of TKE dissipation rate  from
  Kolmogorov's 1941 law \protect\citep{kolmogorov--local.english}, and
  will not be discussed further here.}\linelabel{lin:end-limitations}}


Another problem that eventually emerged is that of flow distortion in
the wake of the acoustic transducers, called transducer
shadowing. Noted first by \cite{kaimal1979sonic}, a specific
correction for the CSAT3 geometry has been proposed by
\cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction}. As observed by them, transducer
shadowing corrections should be applied to all sonic path geometries,
but it may be aggravated in the CSAT3 because of the
transducer-support geometry. They showed that the shadowing effect is
smaller for the \textit{Metek} uSonic-3, for which transducer
corrections are available from the manufacturer
\citep{metek2004flow}. The uSonic-3 has support arms perpendicular to
the transducer, differently from the CSAT3 where they are coaxial, and
that its three sonic paths are at a $45\degree$ angle with the
horizontal. The THIES support geometry is similar to that of the
uSonic-3, except that the paths are at a $60\degree$ angle with the
horizontal. \cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction} point out that the
$60\degree$ geometry is superior to minimize transducer-shadowing
errors. {\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-thiesnoshadow} The
  geometric similarities between the uSonic-3 and the THIES and the
  THIES's $60\degree$ angle indicate that it suffers less from
  transducer shadowing than the CSAT3.  Moreover, according to the
  manufacturer (ADOLF THIES GmbH \& Co. KG, Personal Communication),
  shadowing corrections are already applied in the instrument's
  firmware (without an option to turn them off). Therefore, in this
  work no further shadowing corrections are applied to the THIES sonic
  anemometers.  For the CSAT3s, on the other hand, the optional
  built-in shadowing correction was turned off, and we were able to
  assess the effect of applying the corrections \textit{a posteriori}
  to the measured data\linelabel{lin:aposteriori}.  \linelabel{lin:end-thiesnoshadow}}

{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-moreshadows}
The findings of \cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction} continue to be the
object of further active investigation.  \cite{frank2016all} found
that orthogonal anemometers measured (among others) vertical velocity
standard deviations 8--9\% higher than non-orthogonal ones, justifying
the application of shadow corrections to non-orthogonal sensors.
\cite{frank2016bayesian} reanalyzed the data of \cite{frank2016all} by
mounting a set of anemometers both horizontally and vertically and
applying a Bayesian analysis to minimize the differences between them,
and encountered a correction for the vertical component which was
signficantly higher than the \cite{kaimal1979sonic} correction.
\cite{huq2017evaluation} simulated turbulent flow around a CSAT3
geometry with Large-Eddy Simulation. They found distortion errors in
the vertical velocity of the order of 3--7\%. They studied the effect
of applying both the \cite{kaimal1979sonic} and the
\cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction} corrections, with the latter coming
out slightly closer to the reference values of their simulations.
\cite{mauder2020comparison} compared measurements of a CSAT3 to those
of a bistatic Doppler lidar and, differently from the studies
involving several different sonic anemometers, found that mean wind
velocity and standard deviations of the vertical velocity from the two
sensors were very close.  Finally, \cite{pena2019method} suggested a
further test of the flow-distortion corrections by looking at their
effect on the $4/3$ spectral ratios predicted by local isotropy. They
found that after application of the corrections their USA-1 anemometer
spectral ratios changed for $~1$ to $4/3$, while the CSAT3 ratios
increased at most to $1.2$. In fact, for the CSAT3 the application of
the \cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction} correction had very little
effect: the horizontal transverse to longitudinal ratio was already
close to 4/3, while the vertical to longitudinal ratio ratio remained
barely above 1 (\textit{c.f.} their figure 9).

\linelabel{lin:end-moreshadows}}

Transducer shadowing effects do not exhaust the debate. Lately, it has
been argued that in most comparisons and field studies (among sonics
and also considering the closure of the surface energy budget),
non-orthogonal anemometers (such as the CSAT3 and the THIES compared
here) systematically estimate smaller quantities related to the
vertical velocity component, such as the standard deviation of the
vertical velocity fluctuations $\sigma_w$, and the (virtual) sensible
heat flux $\overline{w'\theta'}$ \citep{frank2020coordinate}. These
authors argue that, for small angles of attack, small transducer
measurement errors can translate into significant systematic errors in
the vertical velocities due to the coordinate transformations involved
in non-orthogonal sonic anemometers.  Clearly, many of these issues
will need further scrutiny. In the present work, we concentrate on
comparison between the two non-orthogonal sonics used in ATTO and the
shadowing corrections \correc{needed}{available} to make their agreement as close as possible.
%% In view of the complexity of the issues, however, it cannot be
%% ruled out that further corrections may eventually emerge as
%% necessary.

\section{Site of experiment}\label{sec:siteexp}


