\section{Data processing methodology}\label{sec:methods}

\linelabel{lin:begin-acquisition}Data are separated in 30-minute
blocks\linelabel{lin:block}, each containing 18\,000 points measured at
10 Hz. \linelabel{lin:end-acquisition}The measurements were
characterized by generally low horizontal wind speeds. The initial
data processing consisted of 3 steps:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Quality control (QC).
  \item Planar fit rotation.
  \item CSAT3 transducer shadowing correction.
\end{enumerate}
{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-shadowplan} Whenever shadowing
  correction was applied, the corresponding planar fit rotation
  matrices were calculated after it.\linelabel{lin:end-shadowplan}
  Moreover, we calculated $u$, $v$, $w$ and $\theta$ spectra as well
  as $uw$ and $w\theta$ cospectra for all blocks that passed QC. In
  Section \ref{sec:results}, $u$ represents the wind velocity
  component along the mean wind direction, $v$ represents the
  cross-wind velocity component, and $w$ the vertical velocity
  component, all after rotation; $\theta$ is the sonic temperature
  also measured by the sonic anemometers. Details are given below.}

\subsection{Quality control}\label{subsec:QC}

{\color{blue}\linelabel{lin:begin-substantially}Quality control is
  similar to that described by
  \cite{zahn.chor.ea--simplemethodologyquality}, who give the
  rationale for its application, but differs in some aspects.  Based
  on \cite{zahn.chor.ea--simplemethodologyquality}'s, we apply 6
  plausibility tests \citep{foken1996tools,taylor2013automated}
  described in the sequence.  First, missing or erroneous raw
  turbulence data (corresponding to the ``complete record'', ``missing
  values'' and ``bounds'' tests of
  \citeauthor{zahn.chor.ea--simplemethodologyquality}) are flagged
  with NaNs \linelabel{lin:nan}(for the definition of a NaN see
  \url{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NaN}).  The next 3 plausibility
  tests flag data for 3 different conditions: ``spikes'', ``locking''
  (a sensor ``locks'' into a very small, unphysical range of values)
  and ``nonstationary'' conditions.\linelabel{lin:end-substantially}}

A data
block is generally referred to as $x_i$, $i=0,\ldots,n-1$ with
$n=18\,000$.  Quality control divides a block with $n$ data points
into $n/m$ sub-blocks with $m$ points each.  We used $m=600$ which
corresponds to 1 minute of data measured at 10 Hz (For the THIES
temperature data, however, $m=6000$; see comments on the THIES
temperature data resolution in section \ref{sec:results}). For each
sub-block we calculate the median $\tilde{x}_s$ and the mean absolute
deviation around it, defined as
\begin{equation}
   \text{MAD}_s = \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=0}^{m-1} \left| x_{sm+i}-\tilde{x}_s\right|,
\end{equation}
where (the sub-block index) $s$ runs from 0 to $n_s-1$, and where $n_s
= 30$ is the number of sub-blocks. A spike is defined as
\begin{equation}
  \left| x_{sm + i} - \tilde{x}_s\right| > n_\delta \text{MAD}_s.\label{eq:spike}
\end{equation}
A ``locking condition'' ($x_i$ varies too little over a sub-block) is
defined as
\begin{equation}
  \max_s \text{MAD}_s < Q_{\text{MAD}}
\end{equation}
Finally, a ``nonstationary condition'' \label{lin:non-stationary} is defined as
\begin{equation}
  \max_r \tilde{x}_r - \min_s\tilde{x}_s > Q_{\tilde{x}}.\label{eq:non-stationary}
\end{equation}


Then the following criteria are applied sequentially:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item If the number of values in the block equal to NaN is more then
  1\% of the block size, \textit{i.e.} $\#(x_i = \text{NaN}) > 0.01n$, then set all
  $x_i$ to NaN and return code 1.
  \item Flag all spikes with NaNs and add to the previous number of
  NaNs. Then, if $\#(x_i = \text{NaN}) > 0.01n$, set all $x_i$ to NaN
  and return code 2.
  \item If $\max_s \text{MAD}_s < Q_{\text{MAD}}$, set all $x_i$ to NaN and
  return code 3.
  \item If $\max_r \tilde{x}_r - \min_s\tilde{x}_s > Q_{\tilde{x}}$,
  set all $x_i$ to NaN and return code 4.
\end{enumerate}
If none of the above occurs, fill all runs of NaNs in $x$ with linear
interpolation from the valid extremeties and return code 0. All blocks
with return code $> 0$ fail QC, and all blocks with return code 0 pass.


