\subsection{Planar fit rotation}\label{subsec:planar-fit}

In turbulence studies and eddy-covariance technique's applications the
mean wind vertical component is assumed negligible
\citep{foken--micrometeorology} and hence a \correc{tilt
  correction}{coordinate rotation}\linelabel{lin:rotation} is applied
to the measured data. This  also includes a rotation of the
horizontal wind velocity components into the mean wind direction. In
the literature, the two most applied techniques are the double
rotation \cite[DR,][]{kaimal.finnigan--boundary.layer.flows} and the
planar fit \cite[PF,][]{wilczak.oncley.ea--sonic.anemometer.tilt}.
While the former rotates the wind vector imposing a null vertical
velocity for each individual block\linelabel{lin:individual}, the latter considers the whole
dataset and rotates the data imposing that the mean vertical velocity
of all measurements is zero; in other words, the planar fit technique
evaluates the plane of the flow streamlines and rotates it into a
coordinate system where the average vertical velocity of the flow is
zero. In sloped terrain or in the presence of complex orography, when
the $w$ axis is not parallel to the acceleration of gravity vector,
the two techniques lead to different estimates of turbulent momentum
and heat fluxes. The tilt correction is crucial in a multi level
experimental site where spectra and cospectra are compared at
different heights \citep{oliveira2018nighttime,correa2021case} or
two-point statistics are evaluated \citep{shaw1995wind,dupont2012momentum}.



\subsection{Path shadowing corrections}\label{subsec:shadow}

{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-explainshadow} As mentioned in the
  Introduction, in this work, when shadowing corrections are applied
  \linelabel{lin:only} (only to the CSAT3s) to data that passed QC , this is always done
  \emph{before} any other processing: in these cases, other procedures
  such as calculation of planar fit rotation matrices and the
  rotations themselves, calculation of means and statistics, etc., are
  performed on the corrected data.  \linelabel{lin:end-explainshadow}}

From the $(u,v,w)$ in an orthogonal system measured by the CSAT3,
we recover the path components
\cite[Eq. (10)]{horst.oncley--correctionstoinertial} from
\begin{align}
  u_a &= -u \cos(\phi) + w\sin(\phi), \\
  u_b &= \frac{u + \sqrt{3}v}{2}\cos(\phi) + w\sin(\phi), \\
  u_c &= \frac{u - \sqrt{3}v}{2}\cos(\phi) + w\sin(\phi),
\end{align}
where $\phi = \pi/3$ is the angle between the CSAT3 paths and the horizontal.
Next, we calculate the instantaneous absolute value of the (uncorrected) wind
vector,
\begin{equation}
S = \sqrt{u^2 + v^2 + w^2},\label{eq:Sfrom-uvw}
\end{equation}
and then, for each path component, the angle between the 
wind vector and that path:
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\alpha} = \arccos(u_{\alpha}/S),
\end{equation}
where $\alpha = a, b, c$. Then the path components are corrected by \citep{horst.semmer.ea--correction}
\begin{equation}
u_{\alpha} := \frac{u_{\alpha}}{0.84 + 0.16\sin(\theta_{\alpha})}.
\end{equation}
where $:=$ stands for the usual assignment in computer languages.
The orthogonal components are then recovered by an inverse rotation
\cite[Eq. (9)]{horst.oncley--correctionstoinertial}:
\begin{align}
  u &= \frac{-2u_a + u_b + u_c}{3\cos(\phi)}, \label{eq:new-u}\\
  v &= \frac{u_b - u_c}{\sqrt{3}\cos(\phi)},\label{eq:new-v}\\
  w &= \frac{u_a + u_b + u_c}{3\sin(\phi)}.\label{eq:new-w}
\end{align}
Note  that the newly recovered $(u,v,w)$ is different from the
raw measurement; therefore, one needs to iterate trough
(\ref{eq:Sfrom-uvw})--(\ref{eq:new-w}) until convergence is achieved
in all components. In this work, the convergence criterion is that the
maximum difference over the three components is less than
$\mathrm{0.001\,m\,s^{-1}}$, which is well below the stated accuracy
($0.01\,\mathrm{m\,s^{-1}}$) of the CSAT3.

{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-refshadow} Campbell's CSAT3B manual
  \cite[][section 7.1.3]{csi--csat3b} mentions that the option to
  apply the shadowing correction uses 3
  iterations. \cite{zhou2018recovery} give a very detailed description
  of the shadowing correction algorithm, and impose, as done here, a
  convergence criterion of $\mathrm{1\,mm\,s^{-1}}$ on each velocity
  component. They report a maximum of 3 iterations until
  covergence. In our case we found that a maximum of 6 iterations were
  needed. \linelabel{lin:end-refshadow}}

\subsection{Spectral analysis}

{\color{blue} \linelabel{lin:begin-spectral} Smooth estimates of
  spectra and cospectra were obtained with a procedure similar to that
  described in \cite{dias--smoothed}; however, in order to more easily
  preserve the typical power laws found in spectra, near-geometric (by
  means of the \textit{log-modulus} and its inverse \textit{exponential-modulus}
  functions; see \cite{john1980alternative}) rather
  than arithmetic running means were used over windows of width 101
  points, and the smoothed spectra were corrected \textit{a
    posteriori} to preserve the areas of the raw spectra (and hence
  the time-domain variances and covariances). Here, our block sizes
  correspond to $B=18{,}000$ points, and the frequencies cover a range
\begin{align}
  f_k &= \frac{k}{B\Delta t}, \qquad k = 0,\ldots,B/2, \\
  \Delta  t &= 0.1\,\mathrm{s}.
\end{align}
The corresponding smoothed spectra and cospectra thus obtained (after
rotation) are $G_{uu}(f_k)$, $G_{vv}(f_k)$, $G_{ww}(f_k)$,
$C_{uw}(f_k)$, $C_{\theta\theta}(f_k)$, and $C_{w\theta}(f_k)$.

Our main focus is on the spectral response of the sensors as well as
in the ability of each sonic to capture the tendency to isotropy in
the higher frequencies corresponding to the inertial subrange. There,
%% \cite[][Eq. 8.4.16]
local isotropy predicts
\citep[Eq. 8.4.16]{kaimal.wyngaard.ea--spectral,tennekes.lumley--first},
\begin{equation}
  \frac{G_{vv}}{G_{uu}} = \frac{G_{ww}}{G_{uu}} = \frac{4}{3}. \label{eq:isotropy}
\end{equation}
Moreover, in order to discern clearly the inertial subrange as well as
high-frequency noise, we plot the compensated spectra
$f^{5/3}G_{xx}(f)$ and cospectra $f^{7/3}C_{xy}(f)$. Finally, we
calculate and show the ``ensemble'' spectra, by
averaging the (co)spectral densities at each
frequency $f_k$ over all blocks.



\linelabel{lin:end-spectral}}



