\subsection{Coordinate rotation}\label{subsec:res-planfit}


Before rotating the data according to the planar fit, the planarity of
the flow was tested. As observed by
\cite{wilczak.oncley.ea--sonic.anemometer.tilt} and
\cite{richiardone2012influence}, if the flow streamlines lie above a
tilted plane, the velocity vector's tilt above the horizontal,
\begin{equation}
  \text{tilt} = \overline{w}\big/\sqrt{\overline{u}^2 +
    \overline{v}^2},\label{eq:tilt}
\end{equation}
 would vary
sinusoidally with the wind direction. The tilt is null when the wind
vector is parallel to the horizontal plane and it assumes its maximum
(minimum) value when it is parallel (anti-parallel) to the $y$-axis of
the planar fit plane. Angular sectors presenting deviations from the
sinusoidal behaviour indicate flow distortion. Figure \ref{fig:tilt}
shows the distribution of the tilt median value evaluated over 16
equally spaced {\color{blue}\linelabel{lin:windbin}22.5\degree-wide
  wind direction sectors} before applying the tilt correction. A
sinusoidal fit of the tilt value depicts the data expected behaviour
without distortions. All the fitting curves present the same trend,
crossing zero and reaching maxima and minima in the same wind
sector. The comparison with the data is worse for wind directions
larger than 180\degree . This is expected, since winds coming from
West (180\degree -- 360\degree ) interact with the Towers's structures
(see Figure \ref{fig:4towers}). Due to their different position
relatively to the tower, the CSAT3-025 and CSAT3-005 present a worse
comparison with the theoretical curve for winds coming from the South
(90\degree -- 270\degree ) and are more likely to be influenced by
flow distortion. In general, all the points lying far from the fitting
curves have a small amount of data, less than 6 points per \correc{bin}{sector}.
\begin{figure}
