\section{Conclusions}\label{sec:concl}

We have conducted a comparison experiment for the two main types of
sonic anemometer deployed at the tall tower (325 m) of the ATTO
project, namely CSAT3s (specifically acquired for turbulence
measurements) and THIESs (in principle acquired for mean wind
profile measurements). Although the THIES is not usually associated
with field studies of atmospheric turbulence, our results show that it
can be used satisfactorily for turbulence velocity measurements,
therefore filling an important role in ATTO; namely, increasing the
vertical resolution of those measurements.

The experiment was conducted under less than ideal conditions, mostly
due to the remoteness of the experimental site, the smallness of the
few existing clearings around the ATTO site, and the timetable for
deployment of the instruments at the tall tower. This resulted in
measurements characterized by low wind velocity and at times high
angles of attack (large values of $\overline{w}/\overline{u}$). On the
other hand, these conditions are common in the flow inside the canopy.

The experiment allowed us to reach some conclusions, related both to
the experiment's conditions and to the use of the sensors at the ATTO
main tower. Specifically to the experiment, we have shown that the
planar fit technique was able to identify the main equivalent slope
direction of the streamlines; indeed, spectra calculated with 2D
rotation showed poorer agreement and behavior (not shown) than those
presented here. An important finding is the corroboration of the
\cite{horst.semmer.ea--correction} proposed correction for the CSAT3,
{\color{blue} and the findings of \cite{frank2016bayesian}, \cite{frank2016all},
  and  \cite{huq2017evaluation}}
at least insofar as it improved the agreement between THIESs
{\color{blue}\linelabel{lin:begin-already}(which already perform
  shadowing corrections internally)\linelabel{lin:end-already}} and
CSAT3s remarkably. Although there is no absolute standard of
comparison in studies of this kind, this result is a strong indication
that the aformentioned correction improves the velocity measurements
by the CSAT3. Therefore, we recommend that is applied to the
corresponding turbulence datasets henceforth measured at
ATTO. \linelabel{lin:begin-csat3worse} \correc{ Moreover, the THIESs
  measurements proved to be more consistent among them than the CSAT3s
  , although this may be weighed against the fact that they were
  installed close together in the middle of each tower, while the
  CSAT3s occupied the extremities.}{} \linelabel{lin:end-csat3worse}




\linelabel{lin:begin-otherhand} \correc{The THIES, on the other hand, is strongly limited by a 0.1 K
  resolution of the sonic temperature.}  {In this study, the THIES was
  limited by software to a 0.1 K resolution of the sonic temperature.}
\correc{This generally bars its use for measurment of weak thermal
  fluctuations.}{This limited its application to measure thermal
  fluctuations.} \linelabel{lin:end-otherhand} However, for the blocks that passed our
(temperature-related) quality control, which are generally associated
with higher sensible virtual fluxes in the middle of the day, it
\correc{may provide}{provided} adequate aditional measurements of
block (30-min.)  statistics related to temperature. \correc{}{In this
  study,} the comparison of temperature-related quantities between the
THIES and the CSAT3 \correc{is}{was} less conclusive: although the
mean temperatures are in \correc{remarkably}{} good agreement, both the
temperature standard deviation and the kinematic heat virtual flux
deviate significantly from a 1:1 line. The disagreement is even more
patent when the corresponding spectral and cospectral densities are
analyzed. It is therefore not possible to reach any definite
conclusion about temperature-related quantities measured by the two
instruments. \correc{At the very least, a carefully planned experiment
  focused on this question is in point.}{Since the
  measurements of the present study were made, we have been able to
  re-program the THIES sonic temperature measurements to a resolution
  of 0.01 K. Further studies comparing the CSAT3 and THIES with better
  temperature resolution will be needed.}

